35. comperendinem=l may commence the second part of tlte action. “After the passing of the Lex Servilia (about B. C. 104), the process in De Repetundis was altogether peculiar, for at that period Comperendinatio was introduced. By this arrangement, all trials De Repetundis were divided into two distinct parts, Actio Prima and Aetio Secunda. In the Actio Prima, the accuser gave an outline of the case; the defender then replicd, and the wit- nesses were examined. The proceedings were now suspended until the next day but one (perendie), when the Actio Secunda took place.” Ramsay's Man. of Rom. Antiqq.
